&gt;print (1 if data in d.values() else 0)

Problem lies here d.values() is not a good way to check if given value is in the dictionary. &lt;br&gt;
Internally Python use Hash function for the *KEY* not for the *VALUE* mapped on that *KEY*. So average case operations may work here in O(1) if you are deleting, updating and inserting *VALUES* by *KEY*. But worst case complexity can be O(N) which can be rare but not ignorable. So your solution is not O(N)&lt;br&gt;

